<doc id="79861" wikidata="Q858237" url="?curid=79861" title="Constant term">
<text>In mathematics, a constant term (sometimes referred to as a free term) is a term in an algebraic expression that does not contain any variables and therefore is constant. For example, in the quadratic polynomial,
:formula_1
The number 3 is a constant term.

After like terms are combined, an algebraic expression will have at most one constant term. Thus, it is common to speak of the quadratic polynomial
:formula_2
where formula_3 is the variable, as having a constant term of formula_4 If the constant term is 0, then it will conventionally be omitted when the quadratic is written out.

Any polynomial written in standard form has a unique constant term, which can be considered a coefficient of formula_5 In particular, the constant term will always be the lowest degree term of the polynomial. This also applies to multivariate polynomials. For example, the polynomial
:formula_6
has a constant term of −4, which can be considered to be the coefficient of formula_7 where the variables are eliminated by being exponentiated to 0 (any non-zero number exponentiated to 0 becomes 1). For any polynomial, the constant term can be obtained by substituting in 0 instead of each variable; thus, eliminating each variable. The concept of exponentiation to 0 can be applied to power series and other types of series, for example in this power series:
:formula_8
formula_9 is the constant term.

==Constant of integration==
The derivative of a constant term is 0, so when a term containing a constant term is differentiated, the constant term vanishes, regardless of its value. Therefore the antiderivative is only determined up to an unknown constant term, which is called &quot;the constant of integration&quot; and added in symbolic form (usually denoted as formula_10).

For example, the antiderivative of formula_11 is formula_12, since the derivative of formula_12 is equal to formula_11 based on the properties of trigonometric derivatives. 

However, the &quot;integral&quot; of formula_11 is equal to formula_12 (the antiderivative), plus an arbitrary constant:

formula_17

because for any constant formula_10, the derivative of the right-hand side of the equation is equal to the left-hand side of the equation.

